N2  - Reviews the book, Trust and Conflict: Representation, Culture and Dialogue by Ivana Markova and Alex Gillespie (see record 2011-23174-000). Trust and distrust are ubiquitous in social life and intergroup relations. But trust is difficult to investigate empirically because, when present, it is largely implicit. This book of essays seeks to move away from the psychological use of statistical studies and experiments for a more contextual, situated analysis of trust and distrust in natural settings. Trust and Conflict provides evidence concerning the importance of context for the validity of experimental findings. Most valuable is the book's suggestion of new ways to investigate the influence of culture and communication on the development of trust and distrust. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
