N2  - This study examined the effects of placing groups at a disadvantage on between group competitive behaviors. Using an intergroup prisoner's dilemma-maximizing difference protocol-participants in small groups were either advantaged or disadvantaged in two experiments. Participants played a game where disadvantaged groups either thought they had to move second in a game in which moving first had advantages (Experiment 1) or were given less money than members of another group (Experiment 2). Results showed that participants whose teams were disadvantaged experienced more negative emotions (envy, jealousy, anger) and consistently responded with more destructive intergroup competitive behaviors. In contrast, groups who were not disadvantaged displayed less between-group competition. While past research has shown that cooperating with in-group members is the typical response in intergroup relations, this study clearly showed that considering whether a group is ahead of or behind other groups is an important consideration. Teams that are behind are more likely to compete against or somehow try to disadvantage teams that are ahead. Winning teams focus more on cooperating with teammates and focus less on disadvantaging other teams. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
