N2  - Comments on an article by C. Morgan and G. Hutchinson (see record 2010-08981-001). Despite evidence implicating social determinants, Morgan & Hutchinson argue in their review that public health has failed to mount a policy-driven response to a seeming epidemic of psychosis in migrant and minority populations in the UK, other European Union countries, and in the USA. Although Morgan and Hutchinson highlight mainly the results from the UK-based AESOP study, the scientific basis on which they call for public health policy is much broader. Evidence implicating racial and ethnic disparities in psychosis exists across a number of nations and marginalized groups. First, social constructs are often conflated. Social adversity differs from socioeconomic disadvantage the underlying social processes may not be the same and more research is needed to differentiate the two with respect to psychosis. Second, there is a need to conceptualize and to measure both risk and protective factors across the life course in etiologic studies of psychosis and other forms of mental illness. Calls for action, like that of Morgan and Hutchinson, provide a necessary and commendable catalyst. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
