N2  - Comments on an article by C. Morgan and G. Hutchinson (see record 2010-08981-001). The review by Morgan & Hutchinson draws attention to the high rates of schizophrenia and other psychotic disorders among certain immigrant groups in Western Europe. We agree with Morgan & Hutchinson that social adversity is the main cause of the high psychosis rates and that sensitization of the mesolimbic dopamine system probably plays a key role in pathogenesis. However, we feel that the concept of social adversity is too broad. If poverty, which is also a form of social adversity, were a risk factor for psychotic disorders, one would expect to find very high rates in developing countries. Morgan & Hutchinson consider 'biological' factors as unimportant, but we believe that illicit drug use may contribute to the development of the epidemic. Since the causes of the epidemic are mainly of a social nature, prevention is primarily a job for politicians, not for psychiatrists. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
