N2  - The face of AIDS in the United States has changed dramatically over the course of the nearly three decades since the disease was first identified. A diagnosis of HIV/AIDS invites stigma, discrimination, and blame and brings fear, anxiety, depression, and isolation. The growing prevalence of HIV/AIDS among impoverished and minority populations translates into enhanced vulnerability for already marginalized, at-risk groups. Although agencies across US are adapting to the changes, the social work literature has yet to address the effects of the reauthorization on social work as a profession. Research is needed to determine the effect that the Ryan White Treatment Modernization Act (RWTMA) is having on the profession of social work and on HIV/AIDS clients. We must bring social work to the table to advocate for HIV/AIDS clients and for policy initiatives that recognize the multifaceted nature of the disease and the comprehensive services needed to deal with it. We must conduct research to determine what is and is not working with the current RWTMA legislation. Social work policy, research, and practice can work in tandem to effect positive change. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
